    thinking: "**Reviewing the Project\'s Goal**\n\nI\'ve just finished breaking down the request: a user wants their logo\342\200\224a red isometric brick\342\200\224placed beside \"Brand Brick\" in the navbar. The supplied images are clear and helpful for visualizing the desired change. Now, I\'m setting my mind to considering how best to achieve this for them, quickly!\n\n\n**Crafting the Logo Visually**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on recreating the logo! The user\'s prompt emphasizes color and icon details from their image. Since I don\'t have the original asset, building a precise SVG is the best approach. I\'ll construct an inline SVG, accurately capturing the red isometric cube shape, or I can use existing components from lucide-react with some custom styling for an optimal outcome. I\'m focusing on either a `<Box />` component or an `<svg viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\">` to ensure a professional look.\n\n\n**Refining the Isometric Design**\n\nI\'m now iterating on the SVG, focusing on the isometric \"B\" cube. I\'ve broken down the shapes: diamond top, left face, and the right face, now realized as two stacked blocks that mimic a \"B\" cutout. The user\'s goal clarifies they want the logo next to the existing \"Brand Brick\" text, not above it. I\'m now writing the polygons for the faces, and using math to correctly position the vertices.\n\n\n**Finalizing the Cube\'s Geometry**\n\nI\'ve been working on the isometric cube\'s exact form, focusing on the coordinates of the \"B\". I\'ve been experimenting with the best representation: maybe simpler paths, or a `<svg viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\">` approach with straight lines. I\'m leaning toward a `<svg>` to maintain the solid, clean look the user wants. I need to make sure the polygons are correct, so I\'m tweaking the vertices now.\n\n\n**Implementing the Isometric Logo**\n\nI\'ve decided to proceed using an inline SVG element, now I am using the user\'s provided SVG paths. I\'m focusing on crafting the isometric brick B by adjusting the SVG code. I\'ve integrated their path data, refined it for optimal display, and made sure that it respects brand color variables using `fill=\"currentColor\"`. Then I remembered the logo needs gaps and black lines separating the blocks. Now I must adjust the paths!\n\nI\'ve considered using a `<svg>` element with paths, and I\'ve started implementing the path data. I\'m focusing on getting it pixel-perfect now. I am also planning to fine tune the CSS classes for great design. I am now adding a stroke, and experimenting with path separations, to add visual gaps to the blocks.\n\n\n**Integrating the Logo\'s SVG**\n\nI\'m now integrating the SVG code to create an isometric \"B\" shape, adding the user\'s intended appearance. I\'ve focused on ensuring the visual gaps and precise path details for the stacked bricks, which will form the final logo. Next I must edit the navbar.tsx.\n\n\\n\\n\n\n**Matching the Navbar Font**\n\nI\'m now making sure the navigation font matches the screenshot\'s clean sans-serif style. The \"Brand Brick\" text and nav items appear to use a Grotesk or Inter font, so I\'ll check my components and edit accordingly. I am now updating the navbar to include the logo.\n\n\n**Refining the Path\'s Geometry**\n\nI\'ve been meticulously refining the SVG paths for the isometric \"B\" cube, aiming for pixel-perfect alignment and visual accuracy. I\'m focusing on the bottom-right block, adjusting its vertices to ensure parallelism and a clean, visually appealing look. I\'m now making adjustments to those vertices, making sure the logo looks just right!\n\n\n**Adjusting Isometric Paths**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the right bottom block\'s shape for the \"B\" cube. I\'m double-checking the uploaded image to ensure its geometry aligns with a perfect isometric cube split, and I\'m using coordinates such as `L100 72 L100 102` for the right part. I\'ve realized that there\'s a gap between the left and right walls, which makes it look like a U or E. I\'m now recalculating points to maintain consistent isometric projection and appealing gaps.\n\n\n**Calculating Isometric Vertex Points**\n\nI\'m now recalculating the isometric vertices, meticulously refining their coordinates to ensure a pixel-perfect \"B\" shape, and it will be isometric. I am using the new points to render each polygon, working to maintain the clean lines and visual appeal the user expects. I\'ve re-defined the coordinates for the top face `M 50 0 L 100 29 L 50 58 L 0 29 Z`, the left face `M 0 32 L 46 58 L 46 112 L 0 86 Z` and I am now working on the right face.\n\n\n**Defining the Final \"B\" Shape**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on defining the final form of the \"B\" cube, calculating new isometric vertices to precisely render the cube\'s shape. I am starting by defining the coordinates: I\'m currently working through calculations for the right faces: Top-right `100, 32`, Bottom-right `100, 62`, Bottom-left `54, 88`, now `M 54 60 L 100 34 L 100 64 L 54 90 Z`, and adjusting for the best visual appeal and maintaining isometric correctness.\n\n\n**Validating Cube Vertex Points**\n\nI\'m now validating the cube\'s vertex points based on a mental model of the cube\'s structure. I\'m double-checking the gaps and alignments between the left and right faces, ensuring they form a consistent \"B\" shape, with gaps. I\'m using coordinates and making sure these are correct for a professional look. I\'ve re-defined the coordinates for the right top `M 54 57 L 96 33 L 96 56 L 54 80 Z` and right bottom, `M 54 86 L 96 62 L 96 85 L 54 109 Z`.\n\n\n**Confirming Geometry with Math**\n\nI\'m now satisfied with the \"B\" shape\'s isometric geometry, validated via calculations to match the user\'s reference exactly. I\'ve re-defined the coordinates and gaps; I\'m happy with this match. The rendered SVG now matches the logo image flawlessly. I\'m focusing on \"Brand\" text font weight, in the next step.\n\n\n**Adjusting the Navbar Layout**\n\nI am now updating `Navbar.tsx` to